1
00:00:00,470 --> 00:00:28,806
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed, Noble and Fully Self-Awakened One.

2
00:00:31,992 --> 00:00:56,463
so what I'm hoping to do is to explain in the Buddha's model as to how the heart heals itself when I say heart, when I use heart during this talk I'm simply talking about your emotional life your moods and emotions both the pleasant and the unpleasant and

3
00:00:58,368 --> 00:01:05,936
This is an area where you'll find that Buddhist practice and modern psychotherapy meet.

4
00:01:07,338 --> 00:01:11,885
And I don't see a problem with that.

5
00:01:13,527 --> 00:01:28,105
But what sometimes seems to happen is that I get a feeling from some books I read that the Buddha didn't actually tackle this problem of our emotional imbalances.

6
00:01:28,388 --> 00:01:40,584
So I just wanted to make it as plain as I can this evening how we create the problems and how we undo them.

7
00:01:45,210 --> 00:01:50,237
The fundamental problem lies with identity as to who we are.

8
00:01:51,640 --> 00:01:57,248
And unsurprisingly, we think of ourselves as human beings.

9
00:01:58,679 --> 00:02:15,735
Unfortunately, having thought of ourselves as human beings on this particular planet and all that, our deepest desire to seek happiness, to be at peace, is sought within the world.

10
00:02:18,478 --> 00:02:27,706
And by making our happinesses and our joys dependent upon the world,

11
00:02:28,835 --> 00:02:56,580
it means that when the world forsakes us then we have all the downside of that particular commitment so for instance if I am attached to my morning cup of tea and I wake up one morning and there is no tea this is potentially a disaster

12
00:02:58,805 --> 00:03:00,507
one feels dreadful.

13
00:03:02,569 --> 00:03:14,063
That dreadfulness is caused because of that conditioning within me which creates morning happiness dependent on English breakfast tea.

14
00:03:18,269 --> 00:03:27,039
At a more solid level of suffering, if my happiness is dependent on my job, on what I do,

15
00:03:27,711 --> 00:03:38,949
If I find myself identifying with that, if and when or when I lose my job, then I go through an identity crisis.

16
00:03:38,968 --> 00:03:46,219
I don't know who I am in society because that's how I've defined myself.

17
00:03:48,903 --> 00:03:56,335
At an even deeper level, there's to do with our relationship to other people, especially those close to us.

18
00:03:58,120 --> 00:04:23,132
And when they let us down, either because they leave us or they die, then I'm stuck with this dreadful pain in the heart, this grief, which I mistakenly think, or I can mistakenly think, is actually the measure of my love, but actually is a measure of my attachment to that person.

19
00:04:24,377 --> 00:04:28,581
Because one good thing about love is that it can let go.

20
00:04:28,622 --> 00:04:31,706
It can allow the person to do what they want to do.

21
00:04:33,608 --> 00:04:46,060
But the grief we feel with the loss is a measure of how much we are dependent on that person for my personal happiness.

22
00:04:46,079 --> 00:04:50,605
And the worst time comes when it's time for me to die.

23
00:04:52,103 --> 00:04:59,870
Because then, however I've defined myself, looks pretty unsteady.

24
00:05:02,892 --> 00:05:05,475
And that's why death comes to us as a great shock.

25
00:05:05,615 --> 00:05:10,639
Because death is saying, whoever you thought you are, you're not.

26
00:05:12,221 --> 00:05:19,747
If you've defined yourself by your body, I am this body, then for sure we're in for a shock.

27
00:05:19,879 --> 00:05:40,225
If you define yourself as, I am this person, I do these things in society, I have these relationships, all this I and how we relate to the I, what death does is, it undermines all those particular self-definitions and dependencies.

28
00:05:43,110 --> 00:05:48,317
So you can see that somewhere deep within our psyche there's a mistake happening.

29
00:05:49,310 --> 00:05:54,535
And it's through this mistake that we form this relationship to the world we live in.

30
00:05:55,855 --> 00:05:58,978
And it's not just identity, it's also possession.

31
00:06:00,800 --> 00:06:09,528
So we form a certain safety, a safety net around us by possessing things, possessing money.

32
00:06:09,588 --> 00:06:17,375
We feel much safer if there's a hundred thousand pounds in the bank and not ten.

33
00:06:17,677 --> 00:06:25,271
So all that psychology around possession, around identity, is a cause of suffering for us.

34
00:06:26,293 --> 00:06:28,476
Because when we lose it, we feel grief.

35
00:06:29,959 --> 00:06:32,244
When we can't get it, we feel frustrated.

36
00:06:33,447 --> 00:06:35,870
And we're constantly afraid we might lose it.

37
00:06:36,762 --> 00:06:45,694
So there's always this underlying anxiety around those things that we're dependent on for our particular happinesses.

38
00:06:46,596 --> 00:06:53,045
Hence, the huge insurance industry.

39
00:06:53,064 --> 00:07:01,317
So, from that position, we formulate a dual relationship to the world.

40
00:07:02,519 --> 00:07:04,862
We either want something

41
00:07:04,942 --> 00:07:05,744
Or we don't want it.

42
00:07:06,144 --> 00:07:07,646
It's extraordinarily simple.

43
00:07:09,389 --> 00:07:13,595
If I like something, if I enjoy something, I try to hold on to it.

44
00:07:13,935 --> 00:07:14,776
I try to keep it.

45
00:07:14,836 --> 00:07:15,937
I try to develop it.

46
00:07:16,999 --> 00:07:19,101
If I don't like it, I try to get rid of it.

47
00:07:19,903 --> 00:07:24,990
If I don't like somebody, I try to take out a contract on that person and just get rid of them.

48
00:07:25,951 --> 00:07:28,375
Thinking that in so doing, I should make myself happier.

49
00:07:28,834 --> 00:07:33,701
It might be a relief, but unfortunately it doesn't tackle the fundamental problem.

50
00:07:34,357 --> 00:07:39,228
So this is the core of our problem.

51
00:07:39,307 --> 00:07:42,675
It's one to do with the question, who am I?

52
00:07:45,461 --> 00:07:51,774
And the essential purpose of insight meditation is really to solve that particular question.

53
00:07:52,970 --> 00:08:13,396
But you can see that from these wrong relationships we formulate or we've begun to develop a whole emotional life, a whole attitudinal life which is creating this inner atmosphere that I feel that often I have to suffer.

54
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:16,581
And

55
00:08:17,978 --> 00:08:23,944
What it's done is it's created habitual patterns within the psyche.

56
00:08:25,446 --> 00:08:29,069
For those of you who know the words, these are what's referred to as your Sankara.

57
00:08:29,571 --> 00:08:31,512
They're things that are put together.

58
00:08:31,834 --> 00:08:34,437
They're sort of accumulations.

59
00:08:34,657 --> 00:08:35,817
Well, that's not quite the right word.

60
00:08:36,118 --> 00:08:43,767
They are inclinations towards a certain type of behavior.

61
00:08:44,471 --> 00:09:02,898
So, if one is in the habit of nipping into Costa coffee or an Americano, and you do it two or three times, it's very difficult to pass Costa coffee without slipping into your Americano.

62
00:09:02,918 --> 00:09:08,385
What is it that generates that sort of compulsive behavior, you see?

63
00:09:09,267 --> 00:09:12,572
And it is what we call these patterns, these habits.

64
00:09:12,754 --> 00:09:17,260
And I personally like them to these programs on a computer.

65
00:09:17,660 --> 00:09:21,846
If you look at your computer, where do these programs exist?

66
00:09:25,009 --> 00:09:29,475
But you press a button and something appears on the screen.

67
00:09:29,535 --> 00:09:33,360
Something takes something out of potential and just manufactures it.

68
00:09:33,881 --> 00:09:40,450
It's a sort of an electrical mechanical habit that if you press this button, the word program appears.

69
00:09:42,657 --> 00:09:44,139
Isn't that similar to us?

70
00:09:45,360 --> 00:09:49,985
You know, we have these buttons, and if they're pressed, we behave in a certain way.

71
00:09:51,147 --> 00:09:58,537
And that this behavior in a certain way manifests the strength of that habit.

72
00:09:59,798 --> 00:10:04,563
And often our response to things tends to be inappropriate.

73
00:10:06,264 --> 00:10:13,634
Now, here's a really sort of crucial point that the Buddha points to in our psychology.

74
00:10:15,076 --> 00:10:32,457
Whatever we experience, whether it's the seeing or the hearing, whatever is done to us by somebody else, whether it's something beautiful or something not so beautiful,

75
00:10:34,345 --> 00:10:45,325
What I feel, what I experience as my response or reaction to that is not caused by the object.

76
00:10:47,809 --> 00:10:56,184
The happiness that I feel when I enter Costa Coffee for an Americano is not caused by the Americano coffee.

77
00:10:56,721 --> 00:11:00,955
All the Americano coffee can do is put a nice taste on my tongue.

78
00:11:01,657 --> 00:11:04,625
That's the contact I have with an Americano.

79
00:11:04,645 --> 00:11:05,006
That's all.

80
00:11:06,230 --> 00:11:10,764
The rest is completely manufactured from within my own psyche.

81
00:11:13,057 --> 00:11:29,620
all the perception of coffee, all the comparison as to whether this coffee is better than Nero's coffee, the whole mentation is all to do with me inside myself and has nothing to do with the coffee that's been poured or the original coffee beans that were picked.

82
00:11:30,500 --> 00:11:34,947
The coffee beans do not cause my mental state.

83
00:11:35,938 --> 00:11:45,650
And my seeking happiness in coffee has produced in me a reaction, a learnt reaction to coffee.

84
00:11:45,811 --> 00:11:50,797
That whenever I smell coffee or taste coffee, happiness immediately arises.

85
00:11:52,238 --> 00:11:55,162
And I think that the coffee is making me happy.

86
00:11:56,123 --> 00:11:56,683
But it's not.

87
00:11:57,605 --> 00:12:04,113
It's my attitude to the coffee that has created this happiness.

88
00:12:04,133 --> 00:12:05,254
Yeah?

89
00:12:05,706 --> 00:12:33,232
if it were not so if it were that the outside world were creating my mental states in terms of the process of liberation I would find myself in an impossible condition because in order to make myself happy this coffee has to be exactly the sort of coffee that I need to make myself happy because this coffee is making me happy

90
00:12:34,613 --> 00:12:41,919
If this person makes me sad, the only way I can get rid of my sadness or my anger is to get rid of this person.

91
00:12:43,282 --> 00:12:43,981
That's very simple.

92
00:12:45,724 --> 00:13:02,780
But if all my mentation, if all my emotional life, if all my thoughts are self-caused, then I should be able to undo those processes within me which are unwholesome.

93
00:13:03,014 --> 00:13:07,240
and continue to develop those processes in me which are wholesome.

94
00:13:08,543 --> 00:13:11,126
And there are wholesome processes to be developed.

95
00:13:12,128 --> 00:13:17,557
Love, compassion, joy, all the beautiful states that we can develop as human beings.

96
00:13:20,822 --> 00:13:27,131
So now, if I perceive that

97
00:13:27,668 --> 00:13:52,157
there's something in me, an attitude, a misunderstanding, well I should say a misunderstanding which creates an attitude, which formulates a relationship, which formulates certain habits, is all conditioned on something that is happening within me, then how am I going to undo

98
00:13:52,205 --> 00:14:03,682
the processes within me which I see as being unwholesome, painful, and to develop those processes in me which I see as actually beneficial and beautiful.

99
00:14:06,106 --> 00:14:11,495
So here, the Buddha's teaching is again very clear.

100
00:14:13,349 --> 00:14:16,052
to talk about the practice of vipassana.

101
00:14:16,452 --> 00:14:31,032
So vipassana simply means insight or just the ability to find a position within ourselves where we can begin to see these misunderstandings and how they're working and what the trigger is that is actually causing the problem.

102
00:14:35,658 --> 00:14:39,863
In the process, we, as it were, turn inwards.

103
00:14:41,057 --> 00:14:42,400
There's an introspection.

104
00:14:42,881 --> 00:14:44,285
But it's not just the looking.

105
00:14:44,746 --> 00:14:47,913
It's a direct contact with what we're actually feeling.

106
00:14:49,418 --> 00:14:52,203
It's a direct experience of our emotional life.

107
00:14:52,706 --> 00:14:54,730
I'm only here talking about emotions.

108
00:14:54,750 --> 00:14:56,754
I'm not talking about the body with pain or anything like that.

109
00:14:56,774 --> 00:14:58,779
I'm just talking about the emotional life.

110
00:15:00,514 --> 00:15:10,169
And as I sit quietly with myself and an emotion arises or a mood arises or a mental state we can call it.

111
00:15:11,172 --> 00:15:17,581
Say something has happened during the day and I'm feeling irritated and I'm sitting with this irritation.

112
00:15:18,604 --> 00:15:20,025
What do I notice happens?

113
00:15:22,429 --> 00:15:25,914
Suddenly I find myself in an argument with this person.

114
00:15:26,366 --> 00:15:39,543
Creating an inner scenario where I'm finally getting my own back This little scenario When I wake up from that I acknowledge so this is the practice of vipassana.

115
00:15:39,682 --> 00:15:55,902
I acknowledge that there is anger I'm not at all concerned With the narrative because the narrative is only a metaphor for the actual presenting emotion the emotion is looking for some way of indulging itself and

116
00:15:57,332 --> 00:16:02,337
It's just stuck here as a volition, a wanting to be angry.

117
00:16:02,677 --> 00:16:07,582
It's got an energy in it that wants to go out and grab an object and murder it.

118
00:16:09,264 --> 00:16:10,225
So there's your anger.

119
00:16:11,086 --> 00:16:21,655
And because you're sitting still and the person whom you're angry with is not there, it wants to create a scenario where it can be fulfilling its particular wishes.

120
00:16:23,197 --> 00:16:24,499
And it does this through thought.

121
00:16:25,539 --> 00:16:26,039
Now,

122
00:16:27,943 --> 00:16:38,599
Something has happened psychologically to move that emotional state into a thought pattern.

123
00:16:38,619 --> 00:16:39,519
Something's happened there.

124
00:16:40,041 --> 00:16:44,586
And it happens so quickly that we don't actually see what that process is.

125
00:16:46,590 --> 00:16:47,730
So the Buddha is very clear.

126
00:16:48,913 --> 00:16:57,124
First of all, there arises a consciousness, a knowing, which contacts that emotional state.

127
00:16:58,167 --> 00:17:00,169
It's the bare consciousness.

128
00:17:00,190 --> 00:17:07,579
And it feels that consciousness as it knows that consciousness as a feeling.

129
00:17:07,760 --> 00:17:09,804
And it perceives it at the same time.

130
00:17:10,003 --> 00:17:14,470
All this is happening in microseconds.

131
00:17:14,490 --> 00:17:18,215
And it also determines whether it's likable or unlikable.

132
00:17:19,156 --> 00:17:23,763
Now, funnily enough, we've trained ourselves to see anger as something quite likable.

133
00:17:25,226 --> 00:17:25,926
Yeah.

134
00:17:25,946 --> 00:17:26,907
Think about it.

135
00:17:27,461 --> 00:17:30,707
Because when you express your anger, there's a feeling of relief.

136
00:17:33,150 --> 00:17:50,075
So this anger now is grasped hold of as a desire to fulfill the desire of the anger, the desire within the anger itself, which is to express itself.

137
00:17:50,095 --> 00:17:54,701
And that desire then becomes identified

138
00:17:55,255 --> 00:17:59,898
We identify with that desire so it becomes I want.

139
00:18:01,180 --> 00:18:06,704
And as soon as that happens, there's another moment where we put energy into it.

140
00:18:07,204 --> 00:18:07,986
And that's the will.

141
00:18:09,366 --> 00:18:14,010
And as soon as we energize that process, we're into a whole set of thinking.

142
00:18:15,692 --> 00:18:16,432
That's what's happened.

143
00:18:18,154 --> 00:18:25,161
And you can, you know, if you're quick enough and you're still enough, you can sit there and watch the beginning of that process

144
00:18:27,502 --> 00:18:43,019
In the Vipassana, what we realize is that when I'm sitting still and just feeling the anger, objectively, but feeling it, there's no suffering.

145
00:18:43,039 --> 00:18:48,526
When I'm aware of the wanting to indulge the anger, there's no suffering.

146
00:18:50,288 --> 00:18:53,612
As soon as I identify with it, suffering arises.

147
00:18:55,786 --> 00:19:09,740
There's a magical moment where the awareness, the mindfulness, consciousness for a better word, I prefer the word knowing, loses itself, as it were, in the process of becoming angry.

148
00:19:11,482 --> 00:19:20,313
And at that point, where we put the energy into that process of mentation, right, we're becoming.

149
00:19:20,452 --> 00:19:23,076
This is what the Buddha means by becoming.

150
00:19:23,291 --> 00:19:26,317
Moment to moment, we recreate the sense of self.

151
00:19:28,402 --> 00:19:36,638
And unwittingly, every time we do that, we empower that particular habit, that particular condition.

152
00:19:37,140 --> 00:19:38,923
So we get more and more.

153
00:19:38,963 --> 00:19:41,509
There's more and more potential for anger.

154
00:19:42,791 --> 00:19:42,872
Huh?

155
00:19:42,892 --> 00:19:42,971
Huh?

156
00:19:44,385 --> 00:19:52,695
Now, you'll all have experienced, I'm sure, sometime in the morning, somebody saying to you something which has slightly upset you.

157
00:19:52,715 --> 00:19:53,156
Nothing much.

158
00:19:54,979 --> 00:19:55,479
Didn't like it.

159
00:19:57,000 --> 00:19:58,864
And then you've put it to the side.

160
00:19:58,903 --> 00:20:00,005
You're not going to be bothered by it.

161
00:20:00,045 --> 00:20:00,986
That's the way they are.

162
00:20:02,607 --> 00:20:03,950
And then you go and have a cup of tea.

163
00:20:04,790 --> 00:20:08,335
And the mind works on it.

164
00:20:08,752 --> 00:20:11,075
while you're eating lunch.

165
00:20:11,816 --> 00:20:13,817
By the time you get home, it's raging.

166
00:20:14,238 --> 00:20:15,159
You have to take an aspirin.

167
00:20:17,401 --> 00:20:20,523
This person only insulted you once, but you've repeated it.

168
00:20:20,644 --> 00:20:35,317
We've repeated it to ourselves a thousand times so that the original little bit of being miffed becomes this huge raging anger, which can only now be revenged by some heinous crime.

169
00:20:36,749 --> 00:20:46,919
All that process was never even originally caused by the person who spoke those cold words to us.

170
00:20:48,380 --> 00:20:55,226
Even the original reaction of being miffed was self-caused.

171
00:20:55,246 --> 00:21:04,494
And we've created this whole world of burning anger all within ourselves and mistakenly determined that they're the problem.

172
00:21:07,731 --> 00:21:17,683
And the whole of the Buddhist psychology brings us back into the realization that it is me that's creating my world.

173
00:21:20,287 --> 00:21:29,798
Even as we walked into this church, this hall, it's not a denial that the hall exists when we're not here.

174
00:21:30,519 --> 00:21:33,823
There is a reality of this hall at a certain level.

175
00:21:34,276 --> 00:21:37,775
But all of us would have had a different experience of this hall.

176
00:21:38,518 --> 00:21:41,855
We're all living in a different hall, actually.

177
00:21:42,730 --> 00:21:44,933
even from what we can see.

178
00:21:44,973 --> 00:21:49,821
I'm completely, I'm living in a very different hall from you people, I can assure you.

179
00:21:49,842 --> 00:21:53,428
I can see the organ for a start.

180
00:21:53,448 --> 00:22:00,159
So everything that I experience is being manufactured by my own psyche.

181
00:22:00,961 --> 00:22:08,333
I like the word psyche because for me it joins the whole mental process of emotions and thoughts.

182
00:22:09,460 --> 00:22:11,021
which actually work together.

183
00:22:11,201 --> 00:22:13,506
It's us that split the two.

184
00:22:14,066 --> 00:22:15,969
The one is always firing off the other.

185
00:22:17,871 --> 00:22:23,739
Now, here's the magic of the Buddha's teaching.

186
00:22:25,741 --> 00:22:30,709
Having developed a certain conditioning, right, we'll stick with anger.

187
00:22:31,269 --> 00:22:35,855
Having developed a certain conditioning of anger, how are we going to get rid of it?

188
00:22:37,522 --> 00:22:48,416
Having now developed it to such a delicate degree how do we now undo this process?

189
00:22:48,436 --> 00:22:55,866
If we try and undo it we find ourselves in contradiction with the given state.

190
00:22:56,647 --> 00:22:58,349
We're trying to get rid of anger.

191
00:22:58,549 --> 00:22:59,852
Have you ever tried to do that?

192
00:23:00,523 --> 00:23:27,509
what you end up doing is pushing it away what you end up doing is suppressing it and worse you end up doing is repressing it because no energy can get rid of this turbulence all you do is you put bad energy into bad energy because you don't want that so what we discover is by allowing the anger to manifest

193
00:23:28,417 --> 00:23:29,340
it cures itself.

194
00:23:29,961 --> 00:23:31,025
It blows itself out.

195
00:23:33,432 --> 00:23:39,548
Now when I say allow the anger to manifest, I'm not talking about allowing it to form thought patterns.

196
00:23:39,568 --> 00:23:43,338
We've already understood that to be a way in which it indulges and grows.

197
00:23:44,787 --> 00:23:52,481
What I'm saying is, what the Buddha says is, sit with it, feel it, allow it to manifest.

198
00:23:52,501 --> 00:23:58,374
And, this is the tricky bit, see how you're relating to this anger, to this feeling.

199
00:23:59,256 --> 00:24:00,258
Does fear arise?

200
00:24:00,739 --> 00:24:01,721
You observe the fear.

201
00:24:02,040 --> 00:24:03,463
Do you think it's going to overtake you?

202
00:24:03,825 --> 00:24:05,007
You observe that fear.

203
00:24:07,196 --> 00:24:08,538
Are you averse to it?

204
00:24:08,798 --> 00:24:10,721
Is there some judgmental thing going on?

205
00:24:10,761 --> 00:24:12,484
I shouldn't be feeling angry.

206
00:24:12,826 --> 00:24:14,769
I'm a bad person because I feel angry.

207
00:24:15,088 --> 00:24:15,849
You observe that.

208
00:24:15,910 --> 00:24:17,673
That's also another conditioning.

209
00:24:20,037 --> 00:24:24,103
Is there a desire to enter into the anger and to develop it?

210
00:24:24,363 --> 00:24:25,124
You notice that.

211
00:24:26,306 --> 00:24:33,356
But all the time you're centering on the feeling that's arising in the body from this conditioning of anger.

212
00:24:34,078 --> 00:24:39,570
Now, you're neither suppressing it, you're not repressing it, and you're not developing it.

213
00:24:40,792 --> 00:24:42,195
So what can this energy do?

214
00:24:42,237 --> 00:24:45,182
It can only exhaust itself.

215
00:24:48,410 --> 00:24:50,615
And that's how the heart heals itself.

216
00:24:51,256 --> 00:24:54,061
You don't actually have to do anything.

217
00:24:56,371 --> 00:25:00,634
Once you've understood that process, that's where your attention goes.

218
00:25:01,215 --> 00:25:03,999
Just to being with the presenting state.

219
00:25:04,459 --> 00:25:12,827
Whether it's anger, depression, anxiety, despair, guilt, shame, the whole gamut of human misery.

220
00:25:14,970 --> 00:25:18,753
All you need to do is attend to it.

221
00:25:19,595 --> 00:25:23,239
And you can even flavor the attending with kindness.

222
00:25:24,703 --> 00:25:28,509
So that you're allowing it to come up and blow away.

223
00:25:31,054 --> 00:25:42,932
Now, when it comes to those things that we enjoy, all the indulgences of life, perhaps we have a problem with overeating, it's the same thing.

224
00:25:44,059 --> 00:25:49,733
When you sit with those particular desires, you find that they're not actually so pleasant.

225
00:25:49,753 --> 00:25:52,441
They're only pleasant when they're being gratified.

226
00:25:53,222 --> 00:25:55,969
To be in a state of thirst is not pleasant.

227
00:25:55,989 --> 00:25:59,959
It's only pleasant because we know when we drink the Coca-Cola, I'm going to feel great.

228
00:26:01,846 --> 00:26:13,419
So to sit with those desires that we see are over the top and to allow them also to express themselves is to take away that conditioning.

229
00:26:14,300 --> 00:26:16,123
And what is that conditioning based on?

230
00:26:16,742 --> 00:26:23,151
It's based on this fundamental misunderstanding that happiness is to be found in the sensual world.

231
00:26:30,239 --> 00:26:31,059
So now,

232
00:26:31,798 --> 00:26:43,854
If we cannot find happiness, and if we can undo all the unwholesome conditionings that we've got, what is it that we're actually moving towards?

233
00:26:44,234 --> 00:26:48,019
What's the process of insight meditation or Buddhist practice?

234
00:26:48,601 --> 00:26:53,267
You don't have to do it sitting, it's just an attitude, it's a way of living.

235
00:26:53,707 --> 00:26:55,950
Where's it actually taking us?

236
00:26:58,849 --> 00:27:10,327
What we find is that by accessing this position of the observer, we are constantly relocating ourselves to a different centre.

237
00:27:12,490 --> 00:27:22,967
When we are a body consciousness, when we think we are the body, then it's very difficult to find any objectivity to the greed and the desires of the body.

238
00:27:24,819 --> 00:27:27,863
How do you experience yourself as a body self?

239
00:27:28,743 --> 00:27:34,770
Well, I mean, as very young children, I think that's what we are, up to about the age of three or something, I don't know.

240
00:27:35,692 --> 00:27:42,920
But when you trap your finger in a door, for that one moment, you are a body.

241
00:27:44,981 --> 00:27:46,924
All you are is that searing pain.

242
00:27:48,125 --> 00:27:50,828
There's no objectivity, one becomes the pain.

243
00:27:51,349 --> 00:27:54,472
That's a wonderful example of being the body.

244
00:27:54,892 --> 00:28:23,058
when you're now by finding this position of observing the body feeling the sensations of the body you relocated out of the body you're not the body because it's an object you can't the object and the subject can't be the same you're feeling the body as an object the sensations keeping more to our emotional state

245
00:28:23,663 --> 00:28:26,066
When do we become emotions?

246
00:28:26,125 --> 00:28:28,188
When are we our emotions?

247
00:28:28,608 --> 00:28:30,810
When we lose ourselves.

248
00:28:30,830 --> 00:28:31,913
When you go into a rage.

249
00:28:31,992 --> 00:28:35,195
When you say to yourself, I am depressed and you're completely lost in it.

250
00:28:36,758 --> 00:28:40,382
When you're anxious and you panic and you run around panicked.

251
00:28:41,443 --> 00:28:44,126
Then you become an emotional self.

252
00:28:44,146 --> 00:28:51,375
There's no distinction between the self and the mental state it finds itself in.

253
00:28:53,211 --> 00:29:01,961
But through this process, one relocates to a different position of the observer, the feeler, the one who knows, the experiencer.

254
00:29:04,243 --> 00:29:13,012
And it's the same with thought, except that thought and images are even quicker than both the body with its sensations and the heart with its emotions.

255
00:29:13,574 --> 00:29:18,679
And so it's even harder to actually be objective about thought.

256
00:29:19,047 --> 00:29:26,586
But at least when we come out of thought, we can see where it is that we've been caught, that what it is we've been caught up in.

257
00:29:27,628 --> 00:29:31,417
And by doing so, we relocate to a different position.

258
00:29:31,939 --> 00:29:33,784
This relocation is the observer.

259
00:29:34,866 --> 00:29:34,946
Huh?

260
00:29:35,652 --> 00:29:49,304
And especially in meditation, but also in daily life, just sitting in a park and just watching, finding yourself in that position, you see, is a point where you discover that there's no suffering.

261
00:29:49,324 --> 00:29:53,508
Now, this isn't the final point, because obviously there's still a sense of self.

262
00:29:56,289 --> 00:30:02,115
If there's a sense of self, you see, then there must be something that knows the self.

263
00:30:04,037 --> 00:30:04,156
Right?

264
00:30:04,728 --> 00:30:07,392
So even that can't be the final position.

265
00:30:08,413 --> 00:30:14,862
How do we experience, you might say, nirvanic or perfectly happy moments in our daily life?

266
00:30:16,684 --> 00:30:34,009
If you put a good intention in your mind to do something and you give yourself to the action, it may be that at first you're aware of yourself doing something and then suddenly there's a loss of that self-awareness.

267
00:30:35,355 --> 00:30:39,680
You might have experienced it doing the garden or a job that you're really interested in.

268
00:30:41,141 --> 00:30:54,313
But you have to be careful because every time you lose yourself in something, if the intention is not pure, then it'll be developing these other types of habits which causes problems.

269
00:30:55,134 --> 00:31:02,080
But if the intention is pure, it'll be developing a habit which is supporting our liberation.

270
00:31:02,800 --> 00:31:03,642
Liberation from what?

271
00:31:03,701 --> 00:31:04,823
Liberation from suffering.

272
00:31:05,359 --> 00:31:06,381
That's all the Buddha's teaching.

273
00:31:07,883 --> 00:31:17,454
And when we enter into those states where we lose a sense of self, when we come out, we also recognize that we've lost a sense of time.

274
00:31:18,655 --> 00:31:21,380
Time and self arise together.

275
00:31:22,800 --> 00:31:31,451
And we also notice when we reflect on that moment, that in the moment where there was no self and no time, we were perfectly happy.

276
00:31:34,182 --> 00:31:50,222
So even in daily life, even in ordinary daily life, we can begin to move towards those places which we know are going to develop this inner sense of peace and happiness, which is not dependent on the outside world.

277
00:31:52,686 --> 00:31:54,469
Not dependent on another person.

278
00:31:55,916 --> 00:31:59,181
And that, you could say, is the process of liberation.

279
00:32:00,422 --> 00:32:07,849
Liberation from the fetter, from the shackles of belief that the world can produce pure happiness.

280
00:32:09,612 --> 00:32:15,077
Now, having said that, does that deny the pleasures and joys of life?

281
00:32:15,357 --> 00:32:15,818
Not at all.

282
00:32:16,759 --> 00:32:21,244
All it's saying is your relationship to them are of a different order.

283
00:32:22,326 --> 00:32:24,067
You neither want to possess them,

284
00:32:24,757 --> 00:32:26,819
nor do you identify with them.

285
00:32:26,839 --> 00:32:28,021
You simply enjoy them.

286
00:32:28,884 --> 00:32:37,557
And the distinction between enjoying something and indulging is extremely subtle and difficult to get.

287
00:32:38,779 --> 00:32:41,924
But in that distinction lies our happiness or lack of it.

288
00:32:43,667 --> 00:32:47,253
And when it comes to those things that we find painful...

289
00:32:48,179 --> 00:32:59,576
When we can sit with patience with them and bear with them in a patient way, we find actually there's no suffering.

290
00:32:59,596 --> 00:33:13,076
So all this suffering, dissatisfaction, unsatisfactoriness, discomfort, all that stuff has never been caused by the world, by anybody else.

291
00:33:13,617 --> 00:33:16,481
It's all been caused within ourselves

292
00:33:16,833 --> 00:33:18,174
by a wrong understanding.

293
00:33:20,258 --> 00:33:35,421
And that wrong understanding is undermined through right practice and through the insights that we get by investigating ourselves through these processes of insight meditation.

294
00:33:35,441 --> 00:33:41,490
And if we do this with a certain commitment, a certain

295
00:33:42,112 --> 00:34:07,680
diligence then hopefully we should see some benefit and it's always possible that we may be fully liberated even in this lifetime but I do not want to give you false hope but at least we can over a period of time feel that there's

296
00:34:08,065 --> 00:34:11,690
A sense of deep meaningfulness about our existence.

297
00:34:12,152 --> 00:34:13,833
That's where the real joy lies.

298
00:34:14,295 --> 00:34:17,559
That we're not here for some peculiar reason.

299
00:34:18,242 --> 00:34:20,786
That there is a deep meaningfulness to our lives.

300
00:34:23,550 --> 00:34:27,315
And that our lives are becoming more at ease.

301
00:34:28,277 --> 00:34:29,579
More at ease.

302
00:34:29,599 --> 00:34:31,163
That we're more contented.

303
00:34:32,465 --> 00:34:34,527
We tend to want peace.

304
00:34:35,166 --> 00:34:39,811
We tend more to want what we get than always get what we want.

305
00:34:43,074 --> 00:34:49,960
And we find ourselves living in harmony with the way things are, even when the way things are are not particularly pleasant.

306
00:34:50,681 --> 00:34:58,588
But you work with them in such a way that they don't cause the old depressions and anxieties of the past.

307
00:34:58,608 --> 00:35:03,452
And these are the telltale signs that we're actually moving spiritually.

308
00:35:06,114 --> 00:35:16,030
And the other great benefit of spiritual progress is the feeling, the growing feeling of connectedness with other beings, with other people.

309
00:35:17,351 --> 00:35:25,242
And that manifests in our kindness and gentleness, in our easy forgiveness, in our compassion, in our sympathetic joy.

310
00:35:26,846 --> 00:35:33,135
And when you feel these things are growing within you, these are the signs to you that you're moving spiritually.

311
00:35:36,186 --> 00:35:43,137
So with those words of hope, I can only hope that my words have been of some assistance.

312
00:35:44,039 --> 00:35:56,300
May you be fully liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

313
00:35:56,960 --> 00:36:00,827
So if there's any questions, brickbacks,

314
00:36:04,047 --> 00:36:11,358
Yeah.

315
00:36:16,367 --> 00:36:16,648
Yeah.

316
00:36:17,789 --> 00:36:23,358
You're finding what one writer calls very happily an observation post within yourself.

317
00:36:24,641 --> 00:36:26,425
It's like a bird watcher.

318
00:36:26,905 --> 00:36:28,547
They find this place, a hide.

319
00:36:28,588 --> 00:36:30,291
They actually call it a hide.

320
00:36:30,422 --> 00:36:35,168
where you can just view the birds and you never interfere, you're just watching.

321
00:36:35,809 --> 00:36:38,072
By the end of it, you can write your bestseller.

322
00:36:38,893 --> 00:36:39,635
So it's the same.

323
00:36:39,956 --> 00:36:57,679
As you find this position in yourself of that little hide of this observation point, which we feel, generally speaking, as the observer, the feeler, the knower, the witness, there's all sorts of words for it, then you begin to understand how your psyche is working.

324
00:37:00,594 --> 00:37:03,681
It's all birds.

325
00:37:03,701 --> 00:37:05,625
Everything.

326
00:37:05,885 --> 00:37:12,177
And what you're trying to see is the connectedness of things and how the one arises dependent on something else.

327
00:37:12,197 --> 00:37:16,726
So you put something sweet on your tongue and your heart becomes happy.

328
00:37:17,007 --> 00:37:22,518
You put something sour on your tongue or something not tasty and you can feel a bit depressed.

329
00:37:25,012 --> 00:37:30,619
The mind comes up, the mind remembers something from the past and suddenly you feel sad, some nostalgia arising.

330
00:37:31,780 --> 00:37:33,822
The mind remembers, and you feel it in the body.

331
00:37:34,061 --> 00:37:35,603
You feel heavy or you feel whatever.

332
00:37:36,704 --> 00:37:43,612
You remember something from the past and it makes you laugh and your body reacts with lovely sensations.

333
00:37:52,820 --> 00:37:53,181
Bless you.

334
00:38:02,644 --> 00:38:20,364
Well, that's right.

335
00:38:20,844 --> 00:38:21,965
Yeah.

336
00:38:22,585 --> 00:38:25,710
How many of you have actually done any insight practice?

337
00:38:25,730 --> 00:38:30,494
How many have not done insight practice of Vipassana?

338
00:38:30,514 --> 00:38:31,655
So you'll be coming tomorrow.

339
00:38:35,347 --> 00:38:41,436
Metta practice is just developing the heart of goodwill.

340
00:38:42,177 --> 00:38:50,570
It's often translated as loving kindness, but that in a sense gives it a feel which is not necessary because you can practice goodwill when you feel horrible.

341
00:38:51,351 --> 00:38:56,659
You can still send out goodwill messages when you don't feel very well.

342
00:38:57,760 --> 00:39:04,409
I think that lady's come.

343
00:39:06,853 --> 00:39:10,641
You'd have to actually do it.

344
00:39:18,132 --> 00:39:21,619
Sometimes if you're watching, so we say, suppose you're watching a cat.

345
00:39:23,922 --> 00:39:28,811
I've just been at a house where there's a cat.

346
00:39:28,831 --> 00:39:32,338
And at first you might just watch it in a sort of disinterested way.

347
00:39:33,465 --> 00:39:42,896
and then somehow you form a relationship with it, you're still watching it, you're still observing what it's doing, but there's a sort of kindness exude towards the cat.

348
00:39:44,878 --> 00:40:02,054
So you're inside yourself and you're watching these feelings, perhaps a nasty one, say you feel a bit depressed, you feel it, but there's as it were within the looking, there's as it were in the contact, there's a feeling of embracing it, opening up to it, a certain kindness towards it.

349
00:40:05,106 --> 00:40:07,789
These things obviously become apparent with the practice.

350
00:40:08,351 --> 00:40:12,735
If you haven't done the practice, it's a bit sort of abstract.

351
00:40:24,168 --> 00:40:28,291
You said towards the end that doing this suddenly your life has meaning.

352
00:40:28,311 --> 00:40:28,853
Not suddenly.

353
00:40:30,193 --> 00:40:30,914
Never suddenly.

354
00:40:33,458 --> 00:40:34,759
Yes, it has meaning.

355
00:40:36,628 --> 00:40:37,809
Yes, right.

356
00:40:38,510 --> 00:40:49,021
Well, normally speaking, the meaning of our lives is dependent upon the life we're living.

357
00:40:49,623 --> 00:40:53,327
It depends on my relationships, on my job, on everything else, you see.

358
00:40:53,967 --> 00:41:06,179
When I begin to realize that these are very untrustworthy meaningfulness things, because they can disappear, I'm seeking for a deeper meaning as to why is it I'm here in the first place?

359
00:41:07,038 --> 00:41:13,706
And what spiritual practice does is it takes you to that core purpose of your being here.

360
00:41:14,286 --> 00:41:17,371
And in Buddhist terms, it's the evolution of consciousness.

361
00:41:18,572 --> 00:41:19,795
It's the evolution of the knowing.

362
00:41:20,715 --> 00:41:24,581
Don't confuse that with the act of cognition, which is a mental thing.

363
00:41:25,202 --> 00:41:33,331
It's that deep knowing within us which is confused with the body, heart and mind complex.

364
00:41:34,527 --> 00:41:40,014
And the process of meditation is the process of extracting that from that confusion.

365
00:41:41,175 --> 00:41:43,617
And in so doing, it discovers its true nature.

366
00:41:50,947 --> 00:42:00,918
And the Buddha refers to it, he tends to refer to it in a slightly negative way, as the unborn, the undying, the uncompounded, the unconditioned.

367
00:42:02,059 --> 00:42:04,163
Which means that it tells us what it's not.

368
00:42:05,137 --> 00:42:10,423
If we were to describe what it is, it puts a concept in our mind and we start searching for it.

369
00:42:10,443 --> 00:42:12,427
You see, a soul, see?

370
00:42:12,447 --> 00:42:17,893
And as soon as you start defining something, it's very difficult not to search for that thing that you've imagined.

371
00:42:19,876 --> 00:42:26,943
But whatever it is, it's beyond the concepts, because concepts are only to do with this particular level of being.

372
00:42:29,876 --> 00:42:41,873
And you'll find that in all vipassana, insight meditation, whether it's that to do with the Theravada school, or the Zen school, or the Tibetan school, all of them tell you to get rid of thinking.

373
00:42:43,076 --> 00:42:43,677
They all tell you.

374
00:42:44,478 --> 00:42:48,804
Zen puts it as no mind, which people think that you might be zonked out or something.

375
00:42:48,824 --> 00:42:49,945
But all they're saying is no thought.

376
00:42:50,786 --> 00:42:52,009
Why should they do that?

377
00:42:52,108 --> 00:42:53,090
Why is that so important?

378
00:42:53,972 --> 00:42:57,436
It's because that's what we are

379
00:42:58,784 --> 00:43:28,487
looking at the world through we're experiencing the world through preconceived ideas when you see a tree you immediately compare it with all the other trees that you've seen just the word tree conjures up ideas with which you look at a tree i remember a teacher used to teach art to children she would take them to a tree and get them to draw the tree and of course they'd all be this stick with a lollipop on top

380
00:43:29,429 --> 00:43:35,036
And then she would get them all to lie underneath the tree looking up and then draw the tree.

381
00:43:35,536 --> 00:43:40,503
And of course, just seeing it from a different perspective produced a much more realistic tree.

382
00:43:43,327 --> 00:43:54,563
Our problem is to go beyond the world that we've constructed through our thoughts and continue to construct through our thoughts.

383
00:43:54,583 --> 00:43:59,250
Even at the basic simple experience of taste, you see,

384
00:44:00,715 --> 00:44:08,342
As soon as we put something, like if you're eating a pizza, you go and order a pizza, you've got an idea of what a pizza is.

385
00:44:09,304 --> 00:44:11,766
And when you get your pizza, it's either a pizza or it's not a pizza.

386
00:44:12,487 --> 00:44:13,509
It's just not a pizza.

387
00:44:14,110 --> 00:44:15,490
This isn't a pizza.

388
00:44:17,112 --> 00:44:23,500
But even those, remember the old, I don't know whether they, they don't seem to sell them anymore, but those old pizzas, they used to sell in plastic bags.

389
00:44:25,420 --> 00:44:39,672
Now, if you'd never had a pizza before and you tasted one of those, you'd have said, at the end of it, you see, and got into it, you'd say, well, that was a rather nice, chewy sort of bread with a hint of tomato.

390
00:44:40,434 --> 00:44:40,956
Very pleasant.

391
00:44:42,940 --> 00:44:44,643
Call it a pizza and it's a disaster.

392
00:44:48,067 --> 00:44:55,697
So our big problem, this is the biggest problem we have, frankly, is to stop thinking, is to see the world without thought.

393
00:44:56,438 --> 00:45:03,186
And we do that by burying the attention in sensation and feeling.

394
00:45:04,548 --> 00:45:05,068
That's what we do.

395
00:45:05,230 --> 00:45:05,931
That's how you do it.

396
00:45:11,838 --> 00:45:14,461
So what is an emotion before you give it a name?

397
00:45:16,403 --> 00:45:16,824
What is it?

398
00:45:19,251 --> 00:45:21,416
What is pain before you call it pain?

399
00:45:22,699 --> 00:45:25,485
That's a mental construct.

400
00:45:25,844 --> 00:45:27,027
There's no pain in the body.

401
00:45:27,429 --> 00:45:28,309
There's only sensation.

402
00:45:29,934 --> 00:45:31,175
Pain is a mental construct.

403
00:45:36,005 --> 00:45:37,429
You can prove this to yourself tomorrow.

404
00:45:51,061 --> 00:45:55,847
Even people whom I deeply love are still objects of my mind.

405
00:45:58,831 --> 00:46:00,554
I can never know them in themselves.

406
00:46:01,054 --> 00:46:02,155
And they can never know me.

407
00:46:03,137 --> 00:46:05,641
All we can form is a pleasant relationship.

408
00:46:07,744 --> 00:46:08,744
A loving relationship.

409
00:46:09,206 --> 00:46:10,306
But I can never know you.

410
00:46:10,628 --> 00:46:12,731
You can never see the world as I see it.

411
00:46:12,811 --> 00:46:15,213
And I'll never see it the way you see it.

412
00:46:15,233 --> 00:46:17,237
In this way we live in parallel universes.

413
00:46:20,980 --> 00:46:23,346
So is there any wonder that we get angry with each other?

414
00:46:46,141 --> 00:46:52,730
The Buddha himself reduced all his teachings to a very simple three-word formula in the original language of Pali.

415
00:46:53,952 --> 00:46:59,818
And it translates as, I teach suffering, unsatisfactoriness, and the end of it.

416
00:47:00,880 --> 00:47:01,201
That's it.

417
00:47:01,442 --> 00:47:05,766
He was only concerned with that area of our lives where we're not happy.

418
00:47:07,309 --> 00:47:09,411
His whole psychology centers on that.

419
00:47:09,472 --> 00:47:11,375
It's not a developmental psychology.

420
00:47:11,956 --> 00:47:15,860
It's all about how do you attain perfect peace and happiness.

421
00:47:20,161 --> 00:47:32,956
And we don't really get on to the spiritual path in Buddhist understanding until we realize that nobody can cause me psychological pain.

422
00:47:39,864 --> 00:47:46,893
This at first comes as a great disappointment because it's been very pleasant blaming others.

423
00:47:50,047 --> 00:47:54,170
But you cannot say to your partner, your spouse, to your friend, you make me angry.

424
00:47:55,032 --> 00:47:56,273
You can't say that anymore.

425
00:47:56,293 --> 00:47:57,594
You make me depressed, you bore me.

426
00:48:04,722 --> 00:48:14,231
